\f1\fs26 \ul \uc0\u8232 \ulnone 29 tests. 2 environments. 1 flag. After 4 hours of Docker hell (previous post), this is the end state. I built a Playwright test suite for OrangeHRM that runs on a shared demo (read-only, 23 tests) and on local Docker (read-write, 29 tests with 6 @local-only). Same code, same assertions. The only difference? `LOCAL=true/false`. **The invariant:** 22 smoke tests passed on both environments \'97 shared demo and local Docker \'97 with zero flakiness. That's what dual-target gives you. **How it works:** `playwright.config.ts` has 3 projects \'97 smoke (CI), chromium (demo), local (Docker) \'97 gated by `LOCAL=true` and Playwright grep tags. 4 tests skipped by design (Claim module missing, no candidates on fresh instance). **Why this matters:** You can't trust demo data. But you can still validate 80% of your smoke suite on the demo \'97 and the @local tests pick up the rest on a real server. **Numbers:** \uc0\u8594  29 unique (23 demo / 29 local) \u8594  22 smoke on both \u9989  \u8594  6 @local. 4 skipped. 0 waitForTimeout in either config. What's your strategy for testing across environments \'97 same suite with tags, or separate configs entirely? Victor Ematin \'b7 AI Quality Engineering Lead \'b7 OpenCode Go #OrangeHRM #Playwright #TestAutomation #QAEngineering #CICD\u8232 \
