\f1\fs26 \ul \uc0\u8232 \u8232 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7469645058896506880?updateEntityUrn=urn%3Ali%3Afs_updateV2%3A%28urn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7469645058896506880%2CFEED_DETAIL%2CEMPTY%2CDEFAULT%2Cfalse%29"}}{\fldrslt 29 tests. 2 environments. 1 flag.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul After 4 hours of Docker hell (previous post), this is the end state.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul I built a Playwright test suite for OrangeHRM that runs on a shared demo (read-only, 23 tests) and on local Docker (read-write, 29 tests with 6 @local-only). Same code, same assertions. The only difference? `LOCAL=true/false`.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul **The invariant:** 22 smoke tests passed on both environments \'97 shared demo and local Docker \'97 with zero flakiness. That's what dual-target gives you.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul **How it works:** `playwright.config.ts` has 3 projects \'97 smoke (CI), chromium (demo), local (Docker) \'97 gated by `LOCAL=true` and Playwright grep tags. 4 tests skipped by design (Claim module missing, no candidates on fresh instance).\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul **Why this matters:** You can't trust demo data. But you can still validate 80% of your smoke suite on the demo \'97 and the @local tests pick up the rest on a real server.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul **Numbers:**\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \ul \uc0\u8594  29 unique (23 demo / 29 local)\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \ul \uc0\u8594  22 smoke on both \u9989 \ulnone \uc0\u8232 \ul \uc0\u8594  6 @local. 4 skipped. 0 waitForTimeout in either config.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul What's your strategy for testing across environments \'97 same suite with tags, or separate configs entirely?\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul Victor Ematin \'b7 AI Quality Engineering Lead \'b7 OpenCode Go\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 }}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com/search/results/all/?keywords=%23orangehrm&origin=HASH_TAG_FROM_FEED"}}{\fldrslt 
