\f1\fs26 \ul \uc0\u8232 \ulnone 29 tests. 11 modules. ~57% coverage. And I'm satisfied. Not because there's nothing left to test. But because structure beats volume \'97 every test maps to a module, a page object, and a traceability matrix entry. What the full suite looks like: \uc0\u9656  12 POMs, 29 test() calls, 22 @smoke \u9656  2 environments (demo + local Docker) \u9656  6 destructive tests running only on local (@local tag) \u9656  4 tests skipped by design (Claim unavailable, admin autocomplete, etc.) \u9656  0 waitForTimeout \'97 every assertion is explicit \u9656  Allure reports on every run, CI/CD on every push, dual-target config \'97 the suite runs itself What I'm not doing: \u9656  Chasing 80% coverage on a shared demo that lies about data \u9656  Writing tests for modules with zero seed data (Directory, Performance, My Info) \u9656  Adding flaky tests that pass "most of the time" What I learned from Buzzhive (292 tests): More tests = more maintenance. Structure beats volume. A passing test on a broken environment is worse than a failing one \'97 because you think you're covered when you're not. Phase 1 gave me bones. Phase 2 added organs. Phase 3 taught me when to stop. \u10067  At what coverage percentage do you ship? 60%? 80%? Or is it about confidence, not numbers? Victor Ematin \'b7 AI Quality Engineering Lead \'b7 OpenCode Go #OrangeHRM #Playwright #TestAutomation #QAEngineering #Coverage\u8232 \
