\f1\fs26 \ul \uc0\u8232 \ulnone Docker Desktop failed. BIOS had to be reconfigured. Here's how I deployed OrangeHRM locally. While building Phase 2, I hit a wall: 25 tests passed on shared demo, but 3 destructive ones needed a real server \'97 add user, add employee, create buzz post all failed on data conflicts. I needed a local instance. What should have been "docker compose up" turned into a saga. The hardware: Windows 10 Pro on a home server. AMD Threadripper X399, 64GB RAM. A workstation never designed for containers. First attempt: Docker Desktop. Engine started timing out after 19 minutes. WSL 2 backend couldn't initialize \'97 a known issue on this chipset. The fix chain: 1. BIOS \uc0\u8594  SVM Mode enabled (M.I.T. \u8594  Frequency \u8594  Advanced CPU Settings \u8594  SVM) 2. Ubuntu WSL 1 \u8594  WSL 2 (required after BIOS change) 3. Docker Desktop uninstalled \u8594  sudo apt install docker.io directly in WSL 2 4. OrangeHRM 5.4 + MariaDB 10.11.4 via docker-compose 5. Installer: 6 green steps, but password policy needed Admin#123 \u8594  MoreSecure#123 6. wget the deployment-runbook from GitHub The networking puzzle: \u9656  localhost:8080 inside WSL \'97 works \u9656  localhost:8080 from Windows browser \'97 doesn't (WSL 2 limitation) \u9656  WSL direct IP 172.xxx.xxx.xxx:8080 \'97 works \u9656  192.168.1.xxx:8080 via netsh portproxy \'97 unstable The SSH tunnel (from MacBook): ssh -L 8080:172.xxx.xxx.xxx:8080 User@10.xxx.xxx.xxx Now I can run Playwright tests from my MacBook against the Windows server. Then all destructive tests pass. Dual-target configuration \'97 three projects: \u9656  smoke \'97 /@smoke/ \'97 runs everywhere \u9656  chromium \'97 excludes @local \'97 CI and demo \u9656  local \'97 /@local/ \'97 LOCAL=true only The result: \u9656  3 destructive tests converted from "expected fail" to pass \u9656  Full suite: 28 tests on local vs 25 on shared demo \u9656  15 smoke tests \'97 every environment \u9656  Zero config changes between environments \'97 just LOCAL=true What this cost me: 4 hours of Docker troubleshooting. 1 BIOS setting. 1 SSH tunnel. 20 lines of config. What I gained: Destructive tests that actually pass. No more wondering if a failure is my code or the demo resetting at 3am. Have you ever had to fight infrastructure just to run a docker compose up? What was the weirdest fix? Victor Ematin \'b7 AI Quality Engineering Lead + OpenCode Agents #OrangeHRM #Docker #WSL2 #Playwright #TestInfrastructure #QAEngineering #OpenCodeDesktopOneLove, Local OrangeHRM installation problems\u8232 \ul \uc0\u8232 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7468572492891189248?updateEntityUrn=urn%3Ali%3Afs_updateV2%3A%28urn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7468572492891189248%2CFEED_DETAIL%2CEMPTY%2CDEFAULT%2Cfalse%29"}}{\fldrslt Docker Desktop failed. BIOS had to be reconfigured. Here's how I deployed OrangeHRM locally.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul While building Phase 2, I hit a wall: 25 tests passed on shared demo, but 3 destructive ones needed a real server \'97 add user, add employee, create buzz post all failed on data conflicts. I needed a local instance.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul What should have been "docker compose up" turned into a saga.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul The hardware: Windows 10 Pro on a home server. AMD Threadripper X399, 64GB RAM. A workstation never designed for containers.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul First attempt: Docker Desktop. Engine started timing out after 19 minutes. WSL 2 backend couldn't initialize \'97 a known issue on this chipset.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul The fix chain:\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul 1. BIOS \uc0\u8594  SVM Mode enabled (M.I.T. \u8594  Frequency \u8594  Advanced CPU Settings \u8594  SVM)\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \ul 2. Ubuntu WSL 1 \uc0\u8594  WSL 2 (required after BIOS change)\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \ul 3. Docker Desktop uninstalled \uc0\u8594  sudo apt install }}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://docker.io/"}}{\fldrslt 
