\f1\fs26 \ul \uc0\u8232 \ulnone I spent 2 weeks testing on a shared demo. Then I discovered the search API was lying to me. --- OrangeHRM OS 5.4 demo version \'97 its search API doesn't filter data. It returns every record every time. My waitForTimeout calls were masking a no-op \'97 tests passed because the first page "looked right." 25 unique tests. 15 smoke. 4 modules built. But 6 `waitForTimeout` were masking a no-op \'97 the API returned everything, the first page just happened to match my search term. I trusted the black box. It was lying. The demo resets data between sessions, blocks destructive operations, and returns 0 employees in Directory search. You can't trust anything it shows you. **So what did I build despite that?** 4 new modules with working tests: - **Recruitment** \'97 load, add candidate, search \uc0\u9989  (3/3 \'97 the only module that accepts new data on shared demo) - **Performance** \'97 load reviews \u9989  (empty, but that's correct \'97 no review data seeded) - **Buzz** \'97 load feed \u9989  | create post \u10060  (demo blocks creation) - **Directory** \'97 load \u9989  (0 employees returned \'97 expected on shared) **Where that gets us:** Phase 1 \u8594  Phase 2: 11\u8594 25 tests, 7\u8594 15 smoke, 5\u8594 11 POMs, 6\u8594 0 waitForTimeout, 22%\u8594 43% coverage, 4/12\u8594 8/12 modules. Metrics of Phase 1 \u8594  Phase 2 ---------------------------------- Tests 11 \u8594  25 Smoke 7 \u9989  \u8594  15 \u9989  POMs 5 \u8594  11 waitForTimeout 6 \u8594  0 Coverage 22% \u8594  43% Modules 4/12 \u8594  8/12 I documented 4 API endpoints \'97 Recruitment, Performance, Buzz, Directory \'97 to make tests data-aware instead of guessing. 4 tests skipped by design: Claim module not available (2), admin autocomplete (1), no candidates on fresh instance (1). 3 more marked `@local` \'97 they only run on local Docker (add user, add employee, create buzz post). Recruitment became the first module at **100% coverage** \'97 because I could actually test it end-to-end on shared demo. **What I learned:** Phase 1 gave me bones. Phase 2 added organs. But the demo taught me something no textbook could: **test what's real, not what's comfortable.** A passing test on a broken environment is worse than a failing one \'97 because you think you're covered when you're not. --- Drop your demo horror story below. Victor Ematin \'b7 AI Quality Engineering Lead #OrangeHRM #Playwright #TestAutomation #QAEngineering #E2E\u8232 \ul \uc0\u8232 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7468542180572237824?updateEntityUrn=urn%3Ali%3Afs_updateV2%3A%28urn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7468542180572237824%2CFEED_DETAIL%2CEMPTY%2CDEFAULT%2Cfalse%29"}}{\fldrslt I spent 2 weeks testing on a shared demo. Then I discovered the search API was lying to me.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul ---\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul OrangeHRM OS 5.4 demo version \'97 its search API doesn't filter data. It returns every record every time. My waitForTimeout calls were masking a no-op \'97 tests passed because the first page "looked right."\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul 25 unique tests. 15 smoke. 4 modules built. But 6 `waitForTimeout` were masking a no-op \'97 the API returned everything, the first page just happened to match my search term.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul I trusted the black box. It was lying.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul The demo resets data between sessions, blocks destructive operations, and returns 0 employees in Directory search. You can't trust anything it shows you.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul **So what did I build despite that?**\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul 4 new modules with working tests:\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul - **Recruitment** \'97 load, add candidate, search \uc0\u9989  (3/3 \'97 the only module that accepts new data on shared demo)\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \ul - **Performance** \'97 load reviews \uc0\u9989  (empty, but that's correct \'97 no review data seeded)\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \ul - **Buzz** \'97 lo