\f1\fs26 \ul \uc0\u8232 \ulnone Webwright: 86.67% state-of-the-art with ~1K lines of code. 8 limitations that decide viability for your stack. \uc0\u9888 \u65039  Microsoft's "terminal-first" agent hits state-of-the-art on Online-Mind2Web and Odysseys (+35% over previous). But real adoption blockers matter more than benchmarks: \u55357 \u56628  Premature "done." Self-reflection gate is mandatory \'97 agent must verify in fresh directory before emitting done:true \u55357 \u56628  Context ceiling. 20-step compaction loses cross-page reasoning. On Odysseys (100-step tasks): GPT-5.4 reaches 60.1% \u55357 \u56628  Script debt. Generated scripts are reusable RPA-style. UI changes kill them silently \'97 requires dedicated validation cycles \u55357 \u56628  Granularity dilemma. Micro-routines (reliable, hard to manage) vs monoliths (comprehensive, fragile). No winner yet \u55357 \u56628  Model ceiling. GPT-5.4 dominates easy tasks (96.2%). Claude Opus wins hard tasks (80.5% vs 76.6%). Your ceiling = your model choice \u55357 \u56628  Environment limits. Canvas, legacy frames, obfuscated UIs force pixel fallback \'97 losing 10x DOM-based speed \u55357 \u56628  TCO amortization. One-time AI generation ($2.37 for GPT or $6.09 for Claude per script) \u8594  near-zero per run after validation. The more regression passes, the lower the cost per test. \u55357 \u56628  Predictability vs resilience. Traditional automation is brittle but deterministic. Webwright is resilient but harder to audit \u55357 \u56516  Each limitation visualized in the carousel below \u55357 \u56391  \u10067  Which one hits your stack hardest? Victor Ematin \'b7 AI Quality Engineering Lead \'b7 $0 budget #Webwright #AITesting #TestAutomation #Playwright #QA, Webwright Reality Check\u8232 \ul \uc0\u8232 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7467832746845847553?updateEntityUrn=urn%3Ali%3Afs_updateV2%3A%28urn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7467832746845847553%2CFEED_DETAIL%2CEMPTY%2CDEFAULT%2Cfalse%29"}}{\fldrslt Webwright: 86.67% state-of-the-art with ~1K lines of code. 8 limitations that decide viability for your stack.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul \uc0\u9888 \u65039  Microsoft's "terminal-first" agent hits state-of-the-art on Online-Mind2Web and Odysseys (+35% over previous). But real adoption blockers matter more than benchmarks:\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul \uc0\u55357 \u56628  Premature "done." Self-reflection gate is mandatory \'97 agent must verify in fresh directory before emitting done:true\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul \uc0\u55357 \u56628  Context ceiling. 20-step compaction loses cross-page reasoning. On Odysseys (100-step tasks): GPT-5.4 reaches 60.1%\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul \uc0\u55357 \u56628  Script debt. Generated scripts are reusable RPA-style. UI changes kill them silently \'97 requires dedicated validation cycles\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul \uc0\u55357 \u56628  Granularity dilemma. Micro-routines (reliable, hard to manage) vs monoliths (comprehensive, fragile). No winner yet\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul \uc0\u55357 \u56628  Model ceiling. GPT-5.4 dominates easy tasks (96.2%). Claude Opus wins hard tasks (80.5% vs 76.6%). Your ceiling = your model choice\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul \uc0\u55357 \u56628  Environment limits. Canvas, legacy frames, obfuscated UIs force pixel fallback \'97 losing 10x DOM-based speed\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul \uc0\u55357 \u56628  TCO amortization. One-time AI generation ($2.37 for GPT or $6.09 for Claude per script) \u8594  near-zero per run after validation. The more regression passes, the lower the cost per test.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul \uc0\u55357 \u56628  Predictability vs resilience. Traditional automation is brittle but deterministic. Webwright is resilient but harder to audit\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul \uc0\u55357 \u56516  Each limitation visualized in the carousel below \u55357 \u56391 \ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul \uc0\u10067  Which one hits your stack hardest?\ulnone 