\f1\fs26 \ul \uc0\u8232 \ulnone \uc0\u55358 \u56800  OrangeHRM: 12 modules, 51 tests, 20% coverage. The math that matters. 20% coverage with a traceability matrix beats 80% without one. I started building an E2E test suite for OrangeHRM \'97 one of the most popular open-source HRMS systems. 12 modules. 51 test cases defined. Only 10 implemented (20% coverage). The gap isn't about "writing more tests" \'97 it's about structure: \u55357 \u56522  Traceability matrix: every test \u8594  module \u8594  page \u8594  POM - Test cases with priorities: Critical / High / Medium - Page Object Model from day 1 (not refactoring later) - Exploration data: 12 modules mapped with screenshots Stack: Playwright + TypeScript + POM \'97 zero dependencies beyond that. What I learned from Buzzhive (292 unique tests, 96% mutation score \'97 repo in comments): - Start with POM, not raw selectors - Traceability matrix saves hours during reviews - Playwright MCP found 12 untested critical paths in 15 minutes Next: 8/12 modules with full traceability \'97 confidence to deploy, not just coverage numbers. \u55356 \u57263  What's your coverage threshold for "confidence to deploy"? 60%? 80%? Or is it something else entirely? Victor Ematin \'b7 AI Quality Engineering Lead \'b7 $0 budget #TestAutomation #Playwright #OrangeHRM #E2E #QAEngineering , E2E Testing for OrangeHRM\u8232 \ul \uc0\u8232 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7467957038459879424?updateEntityUrn=urn%3Ali%3Afs_updateV2%3A%28urn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7467957038459879424%2CFEED_DETAIL%2CEMPTY%2CDEFAULT%2Cfalse%29"}}{\fldrslt \uc0\u55358 \u56800  OrangeHRM: 12 modules, 51 tests, 20% coverage. The math that matters.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul 20% coverage with a traceability matrix beats 80% without one.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul I started building an E2E test suite for OrangeHRM \'97 one of the most popular open-source HRMS systems.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul 12 modules. 51 test cases