\f1\fs26 \ul \uc0\u8232 \ulnone \uc0\u55358 \u56800  5 takeaways from Webwright \'97 Microsoft Research's minimal browser agent (~1,000 lines total) \'97 that changed how I think about browser automation. $2.37 per automation asset. GPT-5.4 authors a reusable CLI tool for $2.37. Pay the reasoning tax once. Run at near-zero cost forever. That number changed what I thought "expensive" automation meant. The common thread? Less is more \'97 fewer lines, fewer clicks, fewer dependencies. **1,000 lines is enough.** Runner (150), Model bridge (550), Terminal sandbox (300). The harness stops being the bottleneck. **Stop clicking, start coding.** Stateless DOM-clickers guess coordinates. Webwright writes Python scripts. The browser is a disposable workspace \'97 the script is the artifact. **Self-reflection beats retries.** Before emitting done:true, the agent runs the script, catches the traceback, fixes imports, then retries in a fresh directory. Terminal stack traces > blind retries. **Less framework = better results.** 86.67% SOTA on Online-Mind2Web. 60.1% on Odysseys (+35%). Claude Opus wins hard tasks (80.5% vs 76.6%). \u55357 \u56516  Full breakdown in the carousel below \u55357 \u56391  Testing Webwright this week. The next post covers what breaks \'97 and what surprised me. Want a reality check? Like \u55357 \u56397  and I'll share what I find. Victor Ematin \'b7 AI Quality Engineering Lead \'b7 $0 budget #AIAgents #Webwright #MicrosoftResearch #TestAutomation #SoftwareEngineering, Webwright Agentic Browser Automation\u8232 \ul \uc0\u8232 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7467137937009442816?updateEntityUrn=urn%3Ali%3Afs_updateV2%3A%28urn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7467137937009442816%2CFEED_DETAIL%2CEMPTY%2CDEFAULT%2Cfalse%29"}}{\fldrslt \uc0\u55358 \u56800  5 takeaways from Webwright \'97 Microsoft Research's minimal browser agent (~1,000 lines total) \'97 that changed how I think about browser automation.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 