\f1\fs26 \ul \uc0\u8232 \ulnone \uc0\u55357 \u56960  How Removing 4,000 Lines of AI Tests Boosted My QA. Best thing I've done all year. 277 unique tests running across 4 browsers \'97 1,108 Playwright runs, plus Python helpers and k6 load. All on a $0 AI budget. API coverage hit 94%. PBT hit 100%. The stack: Playwright E2E suite hitting two environments \'97 Docker (local full stack) and Render (backend-only, free tier). CI/CD runs smoke tests on every push via GitHub Actions \'97 12 endpoints, 3 minutes. Backend had to be stabilised first: exception handlers, connection pooling, uptime monitor. The usual production hardening nobody talks about. Then I looked at the test code. Two monolithic files \'97 3,908 lines of AI-generated spaghetti with 15 duplicated API blocks and no shared fixtures. One sprint later: 23 clean modules, shared fixtures.ts, CI in 3 minutes. The refactoring also found what testing missed: \u55357 \u56347  A race condition that lived in production for a month. Sequential tests couldn't catch it \'97 same microsecond, same JWT, unique_violation in PostgreSQL. Only parallel execution across 4 browser projects exposed the collision. \u55357 \u56593  One line fix: jti: uuid.uuid4(). What the numbers say: \u8594  2 monoliths \u8594  23 modules, ~4,000 lines deleted \u8594  1,108 runs across 4 browsers (277 unique) \u8594  2 environments: Docker (local) + Render (cloud) \u8594  1 race found, 1 line fix \u55356 \u57263  \u8594  15 AI models cycled \'97 6 already gone Free AI is a treadmill. Keep moving or get left behind. Phase 1 recap: https://lnkd.in/dbsecZfm Phase 3 is cooking \'97 Go, C#, mutation testing, Render frontend. Next carousel. \u10067  What's the messiest test suite AI has helped you create? Victor Ematin \'b7 as AI Quality Engineering Lead \'b7 $0 budget #TestAutomation #ZeroBudgetQA #GenAItesting #Playwright #Render #QATips, PHASE 2 \'97 THE REFACTORING SPRINT\u8232 \ul \uc0\u8232 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com