\f1\fs26 \ul \uc0\u8232 \ulnone "Knowledge compounds like interest \'97 the more you use it, the richer it becomes. Follow the principle: don't edit wiki yourself, AI owns the wiki layer." \'97 Inspired by\'a0Andrej Karpathy\'a0and\'a0Nick Spisak We (me and OpenCode \uc0\u55357 \u56507  ) developed a personal knowledge base utilizing the LLM Wiki pattern from Andrej Karpathy (https://lnkd.in/d-zxJ7tX), structured in three layers: raw sources (PDFs, articles), wiki pages (LLM-generated markdown), and a schema (AGENTS. md). Our implementation was for small research about DORA and it included: - Creation of dozen interconnected wiki pages focused on DORA metrics grabbed from several sources - Addition of PNG visualizations (quadrant, comparison, timeline) using Matplotlib - Integration of Obsidian for visual editing and Graph View - Setup of GitHub Pages for public viewing (with noindex) - Utilization of OpenCode and Ollama for Q&A, linting, and content generation Key benefits include: - Knowledge compounding over time, preventing loss in chat history - Cross-linked pages forming a navigable knowledge graph - The LLM maintaining the wiki while humans provide direction - Automatic publishing through Git version control and GitHub Pages - Graph View illustrating relationships between concepts The tools employed in this project were Obsidian, OpenCode, Ollama, GitHub Pages, Matplotlib, and the karpathy/llm-wiki pattern. - We customized OpenCode for our workflow by extending it with persistent memory via ~/.opencode-memory. md and project-specific schemas. - All sessions adhere to conventions, including commit prefixes (feat:, fix:, docs:), checkpoint files at session end, and the exclusion of PAT tokens in commits. - GitHub Pages is configured for all projects with noindex for "link-only" access. - Additionally, we implemented custom scripts: wiki_llm. py for Q&A and linting, dora_charts. py for visualizations, and vision_test. py for image analysis via Ollama. #AI #LLM-wiki #Karpathy #DORA\u8232 \
