\f1\fs26 \ul \uc0\u8232 \ulnone Some team scalability insights from my last startup During 2023-2024, our testing team grew from 2 to 10 people. We faced two key hiring challenges: low candidate quality and low candidate volume, especially given our niche focus on Wi-Fi \uc0\u55357 \u57052  and Linux. 1. Rethinking the candidate profile We realized we were looking for the wrong profile. Instead of a typical QA engineer, we shifted toward network engineers willing to grow into QA. This required building a structured onboarding and training program, along with mentorship from senior team members. The creation of such an educational ladder \u55358 \u56988  is happening quite quickly and is available not only to corporations. As a result, we were able to hire a strong Wi-Fi specialist every 2\'963 months who quickly became productive. 2. Adjusting hiring strategy After reviewing 100+ CVs and conducting 10+ interviews, I moved from a \'93hire slow, fire fast\'94 approach to \'93hire fast, validate fast.\'94 We introduced 3-month probation periods focused on training, mentorship, and performance evaluation, with feedback from the whole team. Only one candidate didn\'92t pass probation due to low contribution and communication gaps. These changes significantly improved both hiring speed and team effectiveness. \u55357 \u56520  #onboarding #mentoring #hire_fast_validate_fast #fast_growing #startup_mindset #scaling\u8232 \ul \uc0\u8232 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7439720173726605312?updateEntityUrn=urn%3Ali%3Afs_updateV2%3A%28urn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7439720173726605312%2CFEED_DETAIL%2CEMPTY%2CDEFAULT%2Cfalse%29"}}{\fldrslt Some team scalability insights from my last startup\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul During 2023-2024, our testing team grew from 2 to 10 people. We faced two key hiring challenges: low candidate quality and low candidate volume, especially given our niche focus on Wi-Fi \uc0\u55357 \u57052  and Linux. \ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul 1. Rethinking the candidate profile\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \ul We realized we were looking for the wrong profile. Instead of a typical QA engineer, we shifted toward network engineers willing to grow into QA.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul This required building a structured onboarding and training program, along with mentorship from senior team members. The creation of such an educational ladder \uc0\u55358 \u56988  is happening quite quickly and is available not only to corporations.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \ul As a result, we were able to hire a strong Wi-Fi specialist every 2\'963 months who quickly became productive.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul 2. Adjusting hiring strategy\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \ul After reviewing 100+ CVs and conducting 10+ interviews, I moved from a \'93hire slow, fire fast\'94 approach to \'93hire fast, validate fast.\'94\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul We introduced 3-month probation periods focused on training, mentorship, and performance evaluation, with feedback from the whole team.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \ul Only one candidate didn\'92t pass probation due to low contribution and communication gaps.\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \ul These changes significantly improved both hiring speed and team effectiveness. \uc0\u55357 \u56520  \ulnone \uc0\u8232 \u8232 }}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com/search/results/all/?keywords=%23onboarding&origin=HASH_TAG_FROM_FEED"}}{\fldrslt 
