\f1\fs26 \ul \uc0\u8232 \ulnone The article "SWE-Tester: Training Open-Source LLMs for Issue Reproduction in Real-World Repositories" discusses the creation of SWE-Tester, an innovative open-source framework designed to train large language models (LLMs) for the automatic generation of issue reproduction tests. Testing is essential in software development, yet many developers find the task of writing tests tedious. Automating the process of reproducing reported issues from their text descriptions could enhance developer productivity and streamline the role of AI in code generation. Current solutions typically depend on proprietary models like GPT-4, leaving the potential of open-source models largely untapped. To tackle this gap, the authors have: - Compiled a high-quality training dataset featuring 41,000 examples derived from real pull requests across 2,600 open-source GitHub repositories. - Developed a two-stage workflow that focuses on localizing defective code and editing test files. - Trained various open-source models, including Qwen-2.5-Coder, Llama3.1-8B, and Gemma3-12B, achieving notable performance improvements\'97up to 10% in error reproduction success and 21% in change coverage compared to baseline models. - Analyzed the effects of scaling training data and enhancing computational resources during the inference stage on AI performance. This research highlights the potential of open-source approaches in software testing, offering a promising alternative to existing proprietary methods. #SWETester #MASpipeline #TestingAI, Technical Report: Advancing Automated Issue Reproduction via SWE-Tester and Multi-Agent Systems (MAS), Victor Ematin on LinkedIn \'95 5 min read\uc0\u8232 \ul \uc0\u8232 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7454564038815989760?updateEntityUrn=urn%3Ali%3Afs_updateV2%3A%28urn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7454564038815989760%2CFEED_DETAIL%2CEMPTY%2CDEFAULT%2Cfalse%29"}}{\fldrslt The article "SWE-Tester: Tr